An =E2=80=9Calgorithmic stablecoin=E2=80=9D sounds complicated, and there a=
re a lot of people with incentives to pretend that it is complicated, but i=
t is not. Here is how an algorithmic stablecoin works[1]:=09You wake up one=
 morning and invent two crypto tokens.=09One of them is the stablecoin, whi=
ch I will call =E2=80=9CTerra,=E2=80=9D for reasons that will become appare=
nt.=09The other one is not the stablecoin. I will call it =E2=80=9CLuna.=E2=
=80=9D=09To be clear, they are both just things you made up, just numbers o=
n a ledger. (Probably the ledger is maintained on a decentralized=C2=A0bloc=
kchain, though in theory you could do this on your computer in Excel.)=C2=
=A0=09You try to find people to buy them.=09Luna will trade at some price d=
etermined by supply and demand. If you make it up on your computer and keep=
 the list in Excel and smirk when you tell people about this, that price wi=
ll be zero, and none of this will work.=09But if you do a good job of marke=
ting Luna, that price will not be zero. If the price is not zero then you=
=E2=80=99re in business.=09You promise that people can always exchange one =
Terra for $1 worth of Luna. If Luna trades at $0.10, then one Terra will ge=
t you 10 Luna. If Luna trades at $20, then one Terra will get you 0.05 Luna=
. Doesn=E2=80=99t matter. The price of Luna is arbitrary, but one Terra alw=
ays gets you $1 worth of Luna. (And vice versa: People can always exchange =
$1 worth of Luna for one Terra.)=09You set up an automated smart contract =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Calgorithm=E2=80=9D in =E2=80=9Calgorithmic stab=
lecoin=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0to let people exchange their Terras for Luna=
s and Lunas for Terras.[2]=C2=A0=09Terra should trade at $1. If it trades a=
bove $1, people =E2=80=94=C2=A0arbitrageurs =E2=80=94 can buy $1 worth of L=
una for $1 and exchange them for one Terra worth more than a dollar, for an=
 instant profit. If it trades below $1, people can buy one Terra for less t=
han a dollar and exchange it for $1 worth of Luna, for an instant profit. T=
hese arbitrage trades push the price of Terra back to $1 if it ever goes hi=
gher or lower.=09The price of Luna will fluctuate. Over time, as trust in t=
his ecosystem grows, it will probably mostly go up. But that is not essenti=
al to the stablecoin concept. As long as Luna robustly has a non-zero value=
, you can exchange one Terra for=C2=A0some=C2=A0quantity of Luna that is wo=
rth $1, which means Terra should be worth $1, which means that its value sh=
ould be stable.All of this is, I think, quite=C2=A0straightforward and corr=
ect, except for Point 7, which is insane. If you overcome that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if you can find a way to make Luna worth some nonzero amount of money =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then everything works fine. That is the whole ballgame. In t=
heory this seems hard, since you just made up Luna. In practice it seems ve=
ry easy, as there are dozens and dozens of cryptocurrencies that someone ju=
st made up that are now worth billions of dollars. The principal ways to do=
 this are:=09Collect some =09transaction fees from people who exchange Luna=
 for Terra or Terra for Luna, and then pay some of those fees to holders of=
 Luna as, effectively, =09interest on their Luna holdings. (Or pay =09inter=
est on Terra, creating demand for Luna that people can=C2=A0exchange into T=
erra to get the interest.[3])=09Talk about building an ecosystem of smart c=
ontracts, programmable money, etc. on top of Terra and Luna, so that people=
 treat Luna as a way to use that ecosystem =E2=80=94=C2=A0as=C2=A0effective=
ly=C2=A0stock in=C2=A0the=C2=A0company=C2=A0that you are building and ascri=
be a lot of value to it.These things reinforce each other: The more fees yo=
u collect and distribute to Luna holders, the more big and viable your ecos=
ystem looks, so the more highly people value it, so the more Luna they buy,=
 so the more activity you have, so the more fees you collect, etc.But there=
 is no magic here. There is no algorithm to guarantee that Luna is always w=
orth some amount of money.=C2=A0The algorithm just lets people exchange Ter=
ra for Luna. Luna is valuable if people think it=E2=80=99s valuable and bel=
ieve in the long-term value of=C2=A0the system that you are building, and n=
ot if they don=E2=80=99t.The danger here is that Point 7 never goes away. A=
ny morning, people could wake up and say =E2=80=9Cwait a minute, you just m=
ade up this all up, it=E2=80=99s worthless,=E2=80=9D and decide to dump the=
ir Lunas and Terras.If people decide to dump their Lunas then the price of =
Luna goes down.If people decide to dump their Terras =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cwait,=E2=80=9D you say, =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s an algorithm; the price=
 of Terra can=E2=80=99t go down.=E2=80=9D If people decide to dump their Te=
rras, then the price of Terra goes down from $1 to like $0.97, and arbitrag=
eurs step in, buy Terras for $0.97 and exchange them for $1 worth of Luna.Y=
eah. Well. The problem is that if people lose confidence in this system, th=
ey decide to dump both Lunas=C2=A0and=C2=A0Terras. Someone sells some Terra=
s. Arbitrageurs step in, buy Terra for $0.99, and exchange it for $1 worth =
of Luna. Luna is at, say, $40, so each Terra gets you 0.025 Luna. Then the =
arbitrageurs=C2=A0sell their 0.025 Luna in the market, which drives down th=
e price of Luna, which is falling anyway. Someone else sells some Terras, b=
ut now Luna is at $20, so each Terra gets 0.05 Luna, which arbitrageurs sel=
l, and now Luna is at $10, so each Terra gets you 0.10 Luna, which then get=
 sold, so Luna goes to $5, so each Terra gets you 0.2 Luna, etc. There is n=
o natural stopping point for this process because=C2=A0Luna is just a thing=
 you made up, and because it represents essentially confidence in your ecos=
ystem, and as the price of Luna crashes that confidence ebbs away. And so e=
ventually Luna trades at $0.0001 and you exchange one Terra for 10,000 Luna=
 and you try to sell them and there are no buyers and so no one wants to ar=
bitrage the price of Terra and so the price of Terra falls below $1 and eve=
ryone gives up on the stablecoin and the ecosystem and everything and it al=
l goes to zero.The technical term for this is a =E2=80=9C death spiral.=E2=
=80=9D Fun fact, that term is also used for something called =E2=80=9Cdeath=
