If a company has $1 billion of debt and only $600 million of value, what ha=
ppens? There is a traditional answer in U.S. bankruptcy law, which goes lik=
e this:=09The creditors =E2=80=94 let=E2=80=99s call them bondholders; let=
=E2=80=99s assume that the $1 billion of debt consists of bonds =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0give up their bonds and get handed the company. Perhaps they run it, =
perhaps they liquidate it, doesn=E2=80=99t matter; in our simple form of th=
e story they just get a thing worth $600 million and their bonds are exting=
uished. Effectively, they are paid 60 cents on the dollar for their debt.=
=09The current equity owners of the company lose it: The company is worth l=
ess than the debt, so the equity goes to zero and the shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0just go away.This is very unpleasant for=
 everyone. The shareholders used to own a company, and now they don=E2=80=
=99t, for a 100% loss. The bondholders paid $1 billion for their bonds, and=
 now they have only $600 million, for a 40% loss. There is no way to sugarc=
oat this. The company is not worth what people thought it would be worth, s=
o they all lost money. It=E2=80=99s bad for everyone because it is bad. The=
 bankruptcy system can=E2=80=99t make it=C2=A0good. All it can do is (1) mi=
nimize the losses (by working efficiently), (2) respect the contractual sen=
iority of claims (by zeroing the equity holders before the bondholders lose=
 money) and (3)=C2=A0share the losses fairly (by making all the bondholders=
 take the same haircut).But there is also a new=C2=A0postmodern=C2=A0answer=
, which=C2=A0goes like this:=09Some=C2=A0of the bondholders get their money=
 back, and a bit more. Say, holders of $501 million of old bonds exchange t=
hem for $551 million of New Cool Bonds that=C2=A0actually pay back=C2=A0$55=
1 million.=09The=C2=A0other=C2=A0bondholders get zeroed. Say, the holders o=
f New Cool Bonds vote to make the other $499 million of old bonds worth zer=
o.=09The current equity owners of the company keep some equity =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0worth $49 million, in this example =E2=80=94=C2=A0and get to continue ru=
nning it.This, you will notice, is much more pleasant for the=C2=A050.1% of=
 the bondholders (who make 10% instead of losing 40%) and for the equity ow=
ners (who keep a $49 million stake in the company instead of losing everyth=
ing). It is much less pleasant for the other 49.9% of the bondholders, who =
lose 100% instead of 40%. This does not respect the seniority of claims (so=
me bondholders get completely hosed even while the equity owners keep their=
 stake), and it certainly does not share the=C2=A0losses fairly (because so=
me bondholders get hosed while others do well). But it does make some peopl=
e=C2=A0happy:=C2=A0Instead of losses, some bondholders have gains; instead =
of losing their company, the equity owners get to keep it. The traditional =
answer makes=C2=A0nobody=C2=A0happy.=C2=A0You can see why the postmodern an=
swer is appealing.I am drastically oversimplifying the postmodern answer =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0you can=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0zero some bondholders while pa=
ying others and leaving the equity intact =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I do think it =
captures the essentials. The company takes value from some bondholders and =
gives it to other bondholders, and in exchange the happy bondholders let th=
e company keep going and maybe find its way out of financial distress. We h=
ave talked about this model  before, most recently  last month. It comes up=
 a lot these days.Here=E2=80=99s the latest from  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Eliza=
 Ronalds-Hannon and Rachel Butt:Envision became the latest firm to stir up =
outrage after the KKR & Co.-owned physician-staffing company secured a $1 b=
illion financial lifeline by shifting its most valuable assets to a new loa=
n, tanking the value of its older debt in the process. =E2=80=A6Late last m=
onth, Envision, struggling with a heavy debt load and pandemic-hit revenues=
, secured a financing package from a group of largely third-party investors=
 including Centerbridge Partners, Angelo Gordon, HPS Investment Partners an=
d Pacific Investment Management Co., according to people with knowledge of =
the transaction.Holders of Envision=E2=80=99s $5.3 billion term loan, inclu=
ding Eaton Vance Corp., Blackstone Inc., SVPGlobal and Sound Point Capital =
Management, instantly saw the value of their debt plunge following the deal=
, which shifted one of Envision=E2=80=99s top assets -- ambulatory services=
 business AmSurg Corp. -- out of their reach. The loan was last quoted at a=
round 53 cents on the dollar, down from as high as 82 cents in February, ac=
cording to data compiled by Bloomberg.Some are already working with legal a=
dvisers ahead of potential litigation, said the people, who asked not to be=
 identified because they=E2=80=99re not authorized to speak publicly. ...Th=
e clash comes after Envision decided to pass on the existing creditors=E2=
=80=99 own financing plan, which would have instead given them claim to AmS=
urg, the people said.Envision rejected that proposal -- which itself would =
have =E2=80=9Cprimed,=E2=80=9D or moved back in line for repayment, any cur=
rent creditors outside the group -- in favor of the third-party deal, which=
 shifted collateral in a manner that the company=E2=80=99s owners and lawye=
rs considered more sound, the people said.=C2=A0Yep. Some of Envision=E2=80=
=99s creditors were like =E2=80=9Cpay us off and hose the other guys, we=E2=
=80=99ll make it worth your while.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Envision turned them down =
and instead took money from a different set of lenders, hosing the first gu=
ys.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s how it works! Somebody is going to get paid and som=
ebody else is not going to get paid. If you are a creditor, the trick is to=
 be one of the ones who get paid. If you are the company, the trick is to s=
tart a bidding war among the creditors to get the best deal possible from t=
he ones who get paid. Playing one group of existing creditors against anoth=
er is a classic way to do that, though Envision managed to get a whole new =
set of lenders to win the bidding war against its existing lenders.The arti=
cle is also good on, like, the self-conception of distressed investors:=E2=
=80=9CTo provide a company with money to work through a tough situation, yo=
u need to be rewarded,=E2=80=9D Glenn August, the chief executive officer o=
f Oak Hill Advisors, said at the recent Milken Institute Global Conference.=
 =E2=80=9CThe documents in some situations allow for that. When you make mi=
stakes, whether it=E2=80=99s with a bad company or bad documents, you suffe=
r the consequences.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0Still, others are critical of the practi=
ce.=E2=80=9CGoing out and pounding each other silly is not our way,=E2=80=
=9D SVPGlobal Chief Investment Officer Victor Khosla said at the conference=
. =E2=80=9CAll this document gamesmanship and the platoons of lawyers, we h=
ave very little time for it.=E2=80=9D ...And in a world where a limited ros=
ter of funds partake in most major transactions, several have found themsel=
ves=C2=A0alternately=C2=A0outraged by priming and asset-transfer maneuvers,=
 and participating in them.=C2=A0Angelo Gordon, which was part of a hedge f=
und cohort that=C2=A0sued=C2=A0Serta in 2020 after it struck a deal to rais=
e fresh cash and push existing creditors down the repayment line, is helpin=
g lead Envision=E2=80=99s new financing this go around.Sometimes you get po=
unded silly, other times you pound silly.=C2=A0By the way, this basic patte=
rn comes up a lot, but often in companies owned by private equity sponsors.=
 There are reasons for this. One is that private equity tends to buy compan=
ies in leveraged buyouts, which means that many private equity companies ha=
ve a lot of debt, which means that they are more likely to run into distres=
s and have to do this stuff. Another is that private equity sponsors are sm=
art, ruthless and repeat players at this game, so they are better at struct=
uring transactions and playing creditors against each other. (And they have=
 the phone numbers=C2=A0of the big creditors so they can make these deals h=
appen.) If you are a big private equity sponsor, one way that you=C2=A0crea=
te value at companies (I mean, for you, and for your limited partners who o=
wn the equity)=C2=A0is by being good at playing creditors against each othe=
r. As distress becomes more common, that=E2=80=99s a good skill to have.
