<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oops</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An =E2=80=9Calgorithmic stablecoin=E2=
=80=9D sounds complicated, and there are a lot of people with incentives to=
 pretend that it is complicated, but it is not. Here is how an algorithmic =
stablecoin works[1]:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left=
: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You wake up o=
ne morning and invent two crypto tokens.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">One of them is the stablecoin, which I will call =E2=80=9CTerra,=E2=
=80=9D for reasons that will become apparent.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The other one is not the stablecoin. I will call it =E2=80=9CLu=
na.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To be clear, they are=
 both just things you made up, just numbers on a ledger. (Probably the ledg=
er is maintained on a decentralized=C2=A0blockchain, though in theory you c=
ould do this on your computer in Excel.)=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">You try to find people to buy them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Luna will trade at some price determined by supply and deman=
d. If you make it up on your computer and keep the list in Excel and smirk =
when you tell people about this, that price will be zero, and none of this =
will work.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But if you do a good jo=
b of marketing Luna, that price will not be zero. If the price is not zero =
then you=E2=80=99re in business.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Y=
ou promise that people can always exchange one Terra for $1 worth of Luna. =
If Luna trades at $0.10, then one Terra will get you 10 Luna. If Luna trade=
s at $20, then one Terra will get you 0.05 Luna. Doesn=E2=80=99t matter. Th=
e price of Luna is arbitrary, but one Terra always gets you $1 worth of Lun=
a. (And vice versa: People can always exchange $1 worth of Luna for one Ter=
ra.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You set up an automated smart=
 contract =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Calgorithm=E2=80=9D in =E2=80=9Calgori=
thmic stablecoin=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0to let people exchange their Terra=
s for Lunas and Lunas for Terras.[2]=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Terra should trade at $1. If it trades above $1, people =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0arbitrageurs =E2=80=94 can buy $1 worth of Luna for $1 and exchange t=
hem for one Terra worth more than a dollar, for an instant profit. If it tr=
ades below $1, people can buy one Terra for less than a dollar and exchange=
 it for $1 worth of Luna, for an instant profit. These arbitrage trades pus=
h the price of Terra back to $1 if it ever goes higher or lower.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The price of Luna will fluctuate. Over time,=
 as trust in this ecosystem grows, it will probably mostly go up. But that =
is not essential to the stablecoin concept. As long as Luna robustly has a =
non-zero value, you can exchange one Terra for=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>quan=
tity of Luna that is worth $1, which means Terra should be worth $1, which =
means that its value should be stable.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">All of this is, I think, quite=C2=A0straightforward and correct, except f=
or Point 7, which is insane. If you overcome that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you can=
 find a way to make Luna worth some nonzero amount of money =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
then everything works fine. That is the whole ballgame. In theory this seem=
s hard, since you just made up Luna. In practice it seems very easy, as the=
re are dozens and dozens of cryptocurrencies that someone just made up that=
 are now worth billions of dollars. The principal ways to do this are:</p><=
ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Collect some <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27678995.284609/aHR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzLnRlcnJhLm1vbm=
V5L2RvY3MvbGVhcm4vZmVlcy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed9fc982" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
=09transaction fees</a> from people who exchange Luna for Terra or Terra fo=
r Luna, and then pay some of those fees to holders of Luna as, effectively,=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27678995.284609/a=
HR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzLnRlcnJhLm1vbmV5L2RvY3MvbGVhcm4vdGVycmEtc3RhdGlvbi9zdGFraW5n=
Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB05b96227" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=09interest on their Lun=
a holdings</a>. (Or pay <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/27678995.284609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW5jaG9ycHJvdG9jb2wuY29tLw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB04efd588" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">=09interest on Terra</a>, creating demand =
for Luna that people can=C2=A0exchange into Terra to get the interest.[3])<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Talk about building an ecosystem o=
f smart contracts, programmable money, etc. on top of Terra and Luna, so th=
at people treat Luna as a way to use that ecosystem =E2=80=94=C2=A0as=C2=A0=
effectively=C2=A0<em>stock </em>in=C2=A0the=C2=A0<em>company=C2=A0</em>that=
 you are building and ascribe a lot of value to it.</li></ul><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">These things reinforce each other: The more fees you collect=
 and distribute to Luna holders, the more big and viable your ecosystem loo=
ks, so the more highly people value it, so the more Luna they buy, so the m=
ore activity you have, so the more fees you collect, etc.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But there is no magic here. There is no algorithm to guarant=
ee that Luna is always worth some amount of money.=C2=A0The algorithm just =
lets people exchange Terra for Luna. Luna is valuable if people think it=E2=
=80=99s valuable and believe in the long-term value of=C2=A0the system that=
 you are building, and not if they don=E2=80=99t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The danger here is that Point 7 never goes away. Any morning, people=
 could wake up and say =E2=80=9Cwait a minute, you just made up this all up=
, it=E2=80=99s worthless,=E2=80=9D and decide to dump their Lunas and Terra=
s.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If people decide to dump their Lunas the=
n the price of Luna goes down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If people de=
cide to dump their Terras =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwait,=E2=80=9D you say, =
=E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s an algorithm; the price of Terra can=E2=80=99t go =
down.=E2=80=9D If people decide to dump their Terras, then the price of Ter=
ra goes down from $1 to like $0.97, and arbitrageurs step in, buy Terras fo=
r $0.97 and exchange them for $1 worth of Luna.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Yeah. Well. The problem is that if people lose confidence in this syst=
