5px;">Priming</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a company has $1 billion of debt an=
d only $600 million of value, what happens? There is a traditional answer i=
n U.S. bankruptcy law, which goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-typ=
e: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">The creditors =E2=80=94 let=E2=80=99s call them bondholders; let=
=E2=80=99s assume that the $1 billion of debt consists of bonds =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0give up their bonds and get handed the company. Perhaps they run it, =
perhaps they liquidate it, doesn=E2=80=99t matter; in our simple form of th=
e story they just get a thing worth $600 million and their bonds are exting=
uished. Effectively, they are paid 60 cents on the dollar for their debt.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The current equity owners of the co=
mpany lose it: The company is worth less than the debt, so the equity goes =
to zero and the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0just =
go away.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is very unpleasant for =
everyone. The shareholders used to own a company, and now they don=E2=80=99=
t, for a 100% loss. The bondholders paid $1 billion for their bonds, and no=
w they have only $600 million, for a 40% loss. There is no way to sugarcoat=
 this. The company is not worth what people thought it would be worth, so t=
hey all lost money. It=E2=80=99s bad for everyone because it is bad. The ba=
nkruptcy system can=E2=80=99t make it=C2=A0<em>good</em>. All it can do is =
(1) minimize the losses (by working efficiently), (2) respect the contractu=
al seniority of claims (by zeroing the equity holders before the bondholder=
s lose money) and (3)=C2=A0share the losses fairly (by making all the bondh=
olders take the same haircut).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is=
 also a new=C2=A0postmodern=C2=A0answer, which=C2=A0goes like this:</p><ol =
style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"><em>Some=C2=A0</em>of the bondholders get=
 their money back, and a bit more. Say, holders of $501 million of old bond=
s exchange them for $551 million of New Cool Bonds that=C2=A0actually pay b=
ack=C2=A0$551 million.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=C2=A0<e=
m>other=C2=A0</em>bondholders get zeroed. Say, the holders of New Cool Bond=
s vote to make the other $499 million of old bonds worth zero.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The current equity owners of the company keep =
some equity =E2=80=94=C2=A0worth $49 million, in this example =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and get to continue running it.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
is, you will notice, is much more pleasant for the=C2=A050.1% of the bondho=
lders (who make 10% instead of losing 40%) and for the equity owners (who k=
eep a $49 million stake in the company instead of losing everything). It is=
 much less pleasant for the other 49.9% of the bondholders, who lose 100% i=
nstead of 40%. This does not respect the seniority of claims (some bondhold=
ers get completely hosed even while the equity owners keep their stake), an=
d it certainly does not share the=C2=A0losses fairly (because some bondhold=
ers get hosed while others do well). But it does make <em>some</em> people=
=C2=A0<em>happy:=C2=A0</em>Instead of losses, some bondholders have gains; =
instead of losing their company, the equity owners get to keep it. The trad=
itional answer makes=C2=A0<em>nobody=C2=A0</em>happy.=C2=A0You can see why =
the postmodern answer is appealing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am dr=
astically oversimplifying the postmodern answer =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can=E2=
=80=99t really=C2=A0<em>zero </em>some bondholders while paying others and =
leaving the equity intact =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I do think it captures the ess=
entials. The company takes value from some bondholders and gives it to othe=
r bondholders, and in exchange the happy bondholders let the company keep g=
oing and maybe find its way out of financial distress. We have talked about=
 this model <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/276789=
95.284609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtM=
