r reach. The loan was last quoted at around 53 cents on the dollar, down fr=
om as high as 82 cents in February, according to data compiled by Bloomberg=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some are already working with legal advis=
ers ahead of potential litigation, said the people, who asked not to be ide=
ntified because they=E2=80=99re not authorized to speak publicly. ...</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The clash comes after Envision decided to pass o=
n the existing creditors=E2=80=99 own financing plan, which would have inst=
ead given them claim to AmSurg, the people said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Envision rejected that proposal -- which itself would have =E2=80=9Cp=
rimed,=E2=80=9D or moved back in line for repayment, any current creditors =
outside the group -- in favor of the third-party deal, which shifted collat=
eral in a manner that the company=E2=80=99s owners and lawyers considered m=
ore sound, the people said.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Yep. Some of Envision=E2=80=99s creditors were like =E2=80=9Cpay us off=
 and hose the other guys, we=E2=80=99ll make it worth your while.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0Envision turned them down and instead took money from a different set=
 of lenders, hosing the first guys.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s how it works! Someb=
ody is going to get paid and somebody else is not going to get paid. If you=
 are a creditor, the trick is to be one of the ones who get paid. If you ar=
e the company, the trick is to start a bidding war among the creditors to g=
et the best deal possible from the ones who get paid. Playing one group of =
existing creditors against another is a classic way to do that, though Envi=
sion managed to get a whole new set of lenders to win the bidding war again=
st its existing lenders.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The article is als=
o good on, like, the self-conception of distressed investors:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CTo provide a company with money to =
work through a tough situation, you need to be rewarded,=E2=80=9D Glenn Aug=
ust, the chief executive officer of Oak Hill Advisors, said at the recent M=
ilken Institute Global Conference. =E2=80=9CThe documents in some situation=
s allow for that. When you make mistakes, whether it=E2=80=99s with a bad c=
ompany or bad documents, you suffer the consequences.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, others are critical of the practice.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGoing out and pounding each other sill=
y is not our way,=E2=80=9D SVPGlobal Chief Investment Officer Victor Khosla=
 said at the conference. =E2=80=9CAll this document gamesmanship and the pl=
atoons of lawyers, we have very little time for it.=E2=80=9D ...</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in a world where a limited roster of funds partak=
e in most major transactions, several have found themselves=C2=A0alternatel=
y=C2=A0outraged by priming and asset-transfer maneuvers, and participating =
in them.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Angelo Gordon, which was par=
t of a hedge fund cohort that=C2=A0sued=C2=A0Serta in 2020 after it struck =
a deal to raise fresh cash and push existing creditors down the repayment l=
ine, is helping lead Envision=E2=80=99s new financing this go around.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes you get pounded silly, ot=
her times you pound silly.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way=
, this basic pattern comes up a lot, but often in companies owned by privat=
e equity sponsors. There are reasons for this. One is that private equity t=
ends to buy companies in leveraged buyouts, which means that many private e=
quity companies have a lot of debt, which means that they are more likely t=
o run into distress and have to do this stuff. Another is that private equi=
ty sponsors are smart, ruthless and repeat players at this game, so they ar=
e better at structuring transactions and playing creditors against each oth=
er. (And they have the phone numbers=C2=A0of the big creditors so they can =
make these deals happen.) If you are a big private equity sponsor, one way =
that you=C2=A0<em>create value at companies </em>(I mean, for you, and for =
your limited partners who own the equity)=C2=A0is by being good at playing =
